fields.title: How can we slash urban heat-island effects and cut cooling-energy demand? Deploy AI-guided “cool roofs” that automatically reflect sunlight based on real-time weather and building data.
fields.description:
Background & Social Impact
Cities are warming twice as fast as the global average, causing heat-related illness, soaring electricity use, and carbon-intensive peak demand spikes. Conventional cool-roof coatings are static: they stay highly reflective even in winter, increasing heating load. A lack of localized, dynamic control wastes energy and limits climate-adaptation benefits.
Functional Goal
Develop a lightweight, AI-driven coating system that combines a tunable reflective membrane with micro-controller actuators to modulate roof albedo (reflectance) in real time—high in hot, sunny hours; low in cold or overcast periods. Integrate rooftop micro-weather sensors and citywide forecasts to optimize each building’s thermal balance and reduce district-level heat-island intensity.
Non-Functional Requirements
• Energy savings ≥ 15 % for cooling and ≤ 5 % penalty for heating vs. baseline roofs
• Retrofit cost ≤ USD 8 per m² including hardware and installation
• System lifespan ≥ 10 years with ≤ 1 % annual maintenance cost
• Operates autonomously offline, with 99 % uptime in −20 °C to 60 °C climates
Known or Suggested Data Sources
• Local rooftop micro-climate sensors (temperature, humidity, solar irradiance)
• NOAA high-resolution weather forecasts and reanalysis data
• City energy-consumption datasets for calibration and validation
Target Impact
Lower peak urban ambient temperatures by 1.5 °C and cut citywide cooling-energy demand by 20 % within five years of citywide deployment.
author: tester

fields.title: 如何预测山区滑坡风险
fields.description:
【Background】山区滑坡对人类生命财产安全威胁严重，尤其在气候变化背景下愈加频繁
【Goal】构建一个模型，基于气象和地形数据预测未来一周的滑坡风险等级
【Non-Functional】模型需具备高召回率（Recall > 0.85），推理时间小于1秒
【Data Sources】遥感影像、历史滑坡记录、降水雷达数据
【Evaluation Preference】以 F1 分数为主要评估指标，次指标包括 Recall、推理延迟等
author: tester

fields.title: 怎么通过图像识别进行垃圾分类？
fields.description:
【Background】垃圾分类一直是环保的难点，耗时耗力。如果能用图像识别方法，到垃圾处场通过机器自动分拣分类，讲极大提高垃圾分类效率
【Goal】根据加拿大的垃圾分类标准，实现混合垃圾的自动分类和分拣
【Non-Functional】实施，识别速度1秒之内，可靠性99%。
【Data Sources】图像识别的通用数据集和专用数据集。
【Evaluation Preference】能实现按垃圾分类标准，实现垃圾的图像分类，从而实现自动化分拣
author: tester

fields.title: How can we detect early-stage diabetic retinopathy in low-resource settings?
fields.description:
Problem Title
How can we detect early-stage diabetic retinopathy in low-resource settings? Use smartphone-based retinal imaging and AI screening to prevent blindness and reduce healthcare inequity.
Background & Social Impact
Diabetic retinopathy (DR) is the leading cause of preventable blindness among working-age adults, yet 50 % of cases are diagnosed too late for effective treatment. Rural and low-income regions lack ophthalmologists, fundus cameras, and reliable internet access. Annual screening rates remain below 20 % in these areas, resulting in irreversible vision loss and soaring long-term care costs.
Functional Goal
Design a portable, AI-driven screening system that captures a retinal photograph with a smartphone-mounted 3D-printed adapter and determines the presence and grade of DR (no DR, mild, moderate, severe, proliferative) within three seconds. Integrate the system into community health-worker workflows and tele-medicine platforms to ensure every diagnosed patient receives timely referral and treatment.
Non-Functional Requirements
• Screening sensitivity ≥ 95 % and specificity ≥ 90 % for moderate-or-worse DR
• Inference latency ≤ 3 s on an offline smartphone (CPU-only)
• Total hardware cost per screening kit ≤ USD 150 (smartphone excluded)
• Operates fully offline; battery life ≥ 6 h continuous use; IP54-rated for dusty, humid clinics
Known or Suggested Data Sources
• Messidor-2, EyePACS, and IDRiD public retinal-image datasets
• Locally collected anonymized images via community health campaigns for domain adaptation
• Patient metadata (age, diabetes duration) to enrich model calibration
Target Impact
Raise annual DR screening coverage to 80 % in pilot regions within three years and cut preventable blindness cases by 35 % within five years of deployment.
author: new

fields.title: How can we make urban traffic lights smarter? Use real-time vehicle flow to set green- and red-time at intersections, raising throughput and cutting delays.
fields.description:
【Background】Rapid population growth has put more cars on the road. Most traffic lights still run on fixed timers, so a red light can stay red even when there is no opposing traffic. This wastes time, increases congestion, lengthens commutes, and raises emissions.

【Goal】Build an adaptive signal-control system that continuously measures vehicle volume on each approach and dynamically adjusts green and red durations. The objective is to raise intersection throughput and lower average wait times, easing city-wide congestion and giving residents back time every day.
【Non-Functional】• System availability ≥ 99 %
• Hardware and installation cost per intersection ≤ USD 10 000
【Data Sources】• Live camera feeds from the intersection
• Historical traffic-volume counts
• Public data sets such as Google Urban Mobility or city open-data portals
【Evaluation Preference】Increase intersection vehicle throughput by 20 % and cut average wait time by 20 %.
author: tester

fields.title: How can we automate waste sorting with computer vision? Use image recognition to classify household trash instantly, boosting recycling rates and reducing landfill use.
fields.description:
【Background】Urban waste volumes are soaring, yet manual sorting is slow, costly, and error-prone. Mis-sorted recyclables contaminate entire batches, leading to more landfill dumping and greenhouse-gas emissions. Citizens often lack clear guidance, resulting in low participation and poor sorting accuracy.

【Goal】Develop a vision-based waste-classification system that captures an image of an item and returns the correct disposal category (recyclable, compost, hazardous, landfill) in under one second. Deploy it on public bins, mobile apps, and collection trucks to raise recycling purity and cut landfill mass.

【Non-Functional】• Classification accuracy ≥ 95 % on the four core categories
• Model inference latency ≤ 1 s on an edge device costing ≤ USD 300
• System uptime ≥ 99 % in outdoor conditions (-10 °C to 45 °C)
【Data Sources】• Smartphone photos collected through a “Snap & Sort” citizen-science app
• Public datasets: TrashNet, TACO, and Waste-LD
• Municipal waste-stream statistics for label balancing
【Evaluation Preference】Increase household recycling accuracy by 30 % and reduce landfill-bound waste by 25 % within two years of deployment.
author: tester

fields.title: How can a tiny digit-recognition model teach high-school students the core ideas of machine learning and advance educational equity?
fields.description:
【Background】Machine-learning literacy is quickly becoming a prerequisite for higher education and the job market, yet many high schools—especially in under-resourced communities—lack the equipment, data, or expertise to offer hands-on ML experiences. A simple, inexpensive project that trains and deploys a digit-recognition model can demystify algorithms, build confidence in STEM, and narrow the opportunity gap.
【Goal】Create a turnkey teaching kit built around a micro-controller–friendly model (≤ 50 kB) that recognizes handwritten digits 0–9 in real time. The kit must include:
A plug-and-play camera or touch-pad input device
Open-source curriculum slides, Jupyter notebooks, and 3 × 45-minute lesson plans
An offline web app (runs in any browser) that shows data collection, training, loss curves, and live inference—no Internet required after initial download

【Non-Functional】• Model accuracy ≥ 90 % on MNIST-test using ≤ 3 training epochs on CPU
• Total hardware cost per student station ≤ USD 20 (micro-controller + camera module)
• Setup time ≤ 10 minutes; teardown time ≤ 5 minutes
• All software must be MIT-licensed, with multilingual support (EN, ES, FR, ZH)
【Data Sources】• MNIST handwritten-digit dataset
• EMNIST letters extension for optional advanced lessons
• Student-generated “classroom digits” collected with the kit for personalization
【Evaluation Preference】After completing the three-lesson sequence, 80 % of participating students can explain—in their own words—the concepts of data, model, loss, and prediction, and 60 % report increased interest in pursuing further STEM courses.
author: tester

fields.name: log_loss
fields.description: Log Loss / Cross-entropy loss (lower is better)

fields.name: top_k_accuracy
fields.formula: \frac{\text{\# samples where true class in top-K}}{N}

fields.name: mse
fields.description: Mean Squared Error (MSE, lower is better)

fields.name: recall_at_k
fields.formula: \frac{\text{\# relevant items in top K}}{\text{\# total relevant items}}

fields.name: coverage
fields.formula: \frac{\text{\# items recommended at least once}}{\text{\# total items}}

fields.description: V-Measure Score (harmonic mean of homogeneity and completeness)

fields.description: Continuous Ranked Probability Score (lower is better)
